      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All FEA solvers (Abaqus 2020, Ansys Mechanical 2021) hold current ISO 9001 certification; version-controlled input decks archived in FDA CDRH repository with audit trail. Gradation 2 requires documented QA plan and version control — both confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Three independent FEA implementations (FDA in-house, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) were executed under documented QA plans. Each solver version was recorded; input files were archived under version control. ISO 9001 certificates on file for commercial codes. Required Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10.1 suite reproduced to within 1% for linear elastic beam bending and contact patch problems. Gradation 2 requires successful execution of standard verification benchmarks — satisfied.",
      "rationale": "Each solver was verified against ASME V&V 10.1 benchmark cases covering linear elasticity and contact. All benchmarks reproduced within 1% relative error. No custom solver modifications were introduced; vendor verification documentation was reviewed and found adequate."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in peak von Mises stress and construct stiffness between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation applied; GCI reported for all three QoIs. Gradation 3 requires quantified discretization uncertainty — confirmed.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh refinement study was performed across three mesh densities (coarse ~80k elements, medium ~240k elements, fine ~720k elements). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values below 1.8% for all three QoIs. The fine mesh was adopted for all production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force-displacement residuals converge to below 1e-5 relative norm; energy balance checked at each load step. Gradation 2 requires documented convergence monitoring — satisfied for all 11 model instances.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear Newton-Raphson iterations converged to residual norm below 1e-5 for all load steps across all 11 model instances. Energy balance was monitored and confirmed. No unconverged increments were accepted."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and load application by a second analyst not involved in model construction. Gradation 2 requires independent review — completed and documented.",
      "rationale": "A second analyst independently reviewed all boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, contact definitions, and load applications against the ASTM F1717 test protocol. Discrepancies were resolved prior to result extraction. Review documented in project record."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic material model was selected for titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) screw and UHMWPE block. Nonlinear geometric effects (large displacement) were included. The compression-bending load case is well within the elastic regime for the metallic components up to yield; post-yield behavior captured via bilinear isotropic hardening calibrated to tensile coupon data. The model form is consistent with established biomechanical literature for ASTM F1717 constructs and was judged adequate for Gradation 3 given the multi-physics scope considered. The rationale for requiring Gradation 3 reflects the moderate complexity of the screw-rod interface contact and the need to capture yield onset accurately for the yield force QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified tensile coupon testing of the same Ti-6Al-4V heat lot; friction coefficients from published tribology literature with uncertainty bounds. Sensitivity analysis shows QoI variation <5% across ±10% input perturbation. Gradation 3 requires quantified input uncertainty — satisfied.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus and yield strength were measured from three tensile coupons from the same material heat lot (mean ± SD reported). Friction coefficient between screw and rod was varied ±20% in a one-at-a-time sensitivity study; stiffness QoI varied by 2.3%, yield force QoI by 4.1%. All inputs traceable to calibrated measurement systems."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot hardware; dimensional inspection confirms screw geometry within drawing tolerances. Two independent laboratories provide inter-lab reproducibility data. Gradation 3 requires statistically characterized sample population — satisfied.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production hardware. CMM dimensional inspection confirmed all critical dimensions within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Testing split across two independent laboratories (n=6 and n=5) to characterize inter-lab variability. Coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.2%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple load magnitudes or configurations tested to span the intended operating envelope; temperature and humidity controlled and recorded throughout. Gradation 3 requires testing across the relevant condition space — only a single ASTM F1717 configuration was tested, yielding Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "All testing was conducted at a single ASTM F1717 configuration (5 mm offset, room temperature, displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min). Only one load configuration was evaluated, limiting the ability to characterize model performance across the full intended operating envelope. This factor was assessed at Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3; the gap is acknowledged and accepted given that ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard for this device class and no alternative configuration is required by the applicable FDA guidance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Model input parameters were mapped directly to experimentally measured quantities: screw outer diameter, rod diameter, and block geometry were taken from CMM inspection reports for each of the 11 constructs. Material properties were matched to the same heat lot. Boundary conditions replicate the F1717 fixture geometry. The correspondence between simulation inputs and physical test parameters was verified by the second analyst during the use-error review. Gradation 2 is considered sufficient given that the primary geometric and material inputs are directly measurable and traceable, and the sensitivity analysis (Model inputs factor) confirms low QoI sensitivity to residual uncertainties."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval computed for each QoI; E/uval < 1.96 required for acceptance. Percent difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean must be <10% for all three QoIs. Gradation 3 requires uncertainty-normalized comparison — satisfied for stiffness and force at 40 mm; yield force E/uval = 1.71.",
      "rationale": "The validation error E was computed as the difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean; uval is the combined experimental uncertainty (inter-lab + measurement). E/uval values: stiffness 0.83, yield force 1.71, force at 40 mm 1.12. All below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences: stiffness 3.1%, yield force 7.8%, force at 40 mm 4.4%. All within the 10% acceptance bound."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical failure modes identified in the risk analysis (fatigue fracture, permanent deformation). Traceability matrix from QoI to design requirement documented. Gradation 3 requires demonstrated QoI-to-COU relevance — satisfied.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs were selected based on the ASTM F1717 standard and mapped to clinical failure modes in the device risk analysis: construct stiffness relates to load sharing with the spine, yield force to permanent deformation risk, and force at 40 mm to fracture risk under extreme loading. A formal traceability matrix links each QoI to at least one design requirement in the device DHF."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use production-equivalent hardware, regulatory-standard test protocol (ASTM F1717), and clinically representative loading magnitudes. Gradation 3 requires high relevance of validation scenario to intended COU — satisfied.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities were conducted using production-lot hardware under the ASTM F1717 protocol, which is the FDA-recognized standard for pedicle screw construct mechanical testing. Loading magnitudes and boundary conditions are representative of the clinical compression-bending environment. The validation scenario is therefore directly relevant to the COU, supporting high confidence in the model's predictive capability for the intended regulatory submission."
    }
  ],
